<span id="freeTextContainer17466879888154223755">There are major spoilers in this review, so skip that section if you don&apos;t want to know.<br/><br/>I had read other books by Francine Rivers and enjoyed them a lot, so I wanted to read another. I picked this one since it had such a high rating and my local public library had it. Bad choice. It was very unrealistic, IMO. <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[Leota had to work outside the home from the time her children were very young in order to provide for the family, since nobody else in the family could do it. Instead of tell</span></span>
  <span id="freeText17466879888154223755" style="display:none">There are major spoilers in this review, so skip that section if you don't want to know.<br /><br />I had read other books by Francine Rivers and enjoyed them a lot, so I wanted to read another. I picked this one since it had such a high rating and my local public library had it. Bad choice. It was very unrealistic, IMO. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Leota had to work outside the home from the time her children were very young in order to provide for the family, since nobody else in the family could do it. Instead of telling her children when they were little the reasons she had to work outside the home and the reason she worked in the garden whenever she was home instead of helping care for the kids and home, Leota kept silent and let her children hate her, knowing full well that that was what was happening. The hate and bitterness of the children just grew and grew without Leota trying to explain anything until the children were grown and wouldn't listen to any explanations. Supposedly she loved the children greatly and was very grieved right from the start that her children were feeling unloved by her, but she did nothing to change that. I just don't believe that someone who loves her children so much would allow that to happen. <br /><br />The "mercy killing" of Leota irritated me, especially since the author could have easily had her die of natural causes. The murder was not discovered, and the murderer just went on his merry way so that he could murder other old people in the future. I guess the only reason it was in there was so the author could show that a suffering elderly person may have a strong desire to live and not want to be put out of her misery and that "mercy killing" is murder.<br /><br />The daughter finally realized how wrong she had been all those decades and was ready to reconcile with her mother in the morning, but Leota was murdered during the night. So much for reading about a reconciliation that I was expecting and hoping for. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I didn't like several things about the ending. Things were left hanging. <br /><br />The timeline thing bothered me somewhat, although it wouldn't be enough to make me dislike the book. I think the setting of the book should have been more than a decade earlier than the book copyright.</span>
